\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces A fibre-loop architecture for implementing arbitrary linear optics operations upon a time-bin-encoded pulse-train. The source prepares the temporally encoded pulse-train, with time-bin separation $\tau $. The pulse-train then enters a dual-loop configuration. The inner loop has length exactly $\tau $, while the outer one has length $>n\tau $ ($n$ is the number of optical modes). The architecture is controlled via three dynamically controlled beamsplitters. The first and last need only be on/off switches, whose sole purpose is to couple in the prepared pulse-train, keep it within the outer loop for the required duration, and then couple out of the outer loop, yielding the transformed pulse-train. The central beamsplitter must be able to implement arbitrary classically-controlled beamsplitter operations.}}{8}{figure.4}}
\newlabel{fig:FL_arch}{{4}{8}{A fibre-loop architecture for implementing arbitrary linear optics operations upon a time-bin-encoded pulse-train. The source prepares the temporally encoded pulse-train, with time-bin separation $\tau $. The pulse-train then enters a dual-loop configuration. The inner loop has length exactly $\tau $, while the outer one has length $>n\tau $ ($n$ is the number of optical modes). The architecture is controlled via three dynamically controlled beamsplitters. The first and last need only be on/off switches, whose sole purpose is to couple in the prepared pulse-train, keep it within the outer loop for the required duration, and then couple out of the outer loop, yielding the transformed pulse-train. The central beamsplitter must be able to implement arbitrary classically-controlled beamsplitter operations}{figure.4}{}}
